  "prompt": "How did the ring come to Sauron?",
  "response": "In J.R.R. Tolkien's mythology, the One Ring was originally created by the Dark Lord Sauron in the Second Age of Middle-earth. Sauron forged the Ring in the fires of Mount Doom in Mordor as a tool to control the other Rings of Power and dominate the free peoples of Middle-earth. \n\nHe secretly crafted the Ring while the Elven-smiths of Eregion, led by Celebrimbor, were creating the Rings of Power. When the Elves realized Sauron's true nature, they removed their Rings and hid them. Sauron then waged war to recover the Rings, eventually obtaining most of them.\n\nHowever, the Ring was cut from Sauron's hand by Isildur during the Battle of the Last Alliance, when Sauron was defeated. Instead of destroying the Ring, Isildur kept it. The Ring later betrayed Isildur, causing him to be killed by Orcs, and was lost in the Gladden Fields.\n\nCenturies later, the creature Gollum found the Ring and possessed it for hundreds of years before losing it, which led to Bilbo Baggins finding it during his adventures, setting the stage for the events of \"The Lord of the Rings.\"",
